The RE team manages all releases into production managing more than 200 releases into production every month. High automation is the key to operate at such high scale where the Engineering Services team is responsible for automating most of the activities starting from code checks to releases.
DM Operations -

Data Management Operations owns all the production jobs transforming and loading data across several platforms coming from PayPal sites and other third party vendors. Platforms include TeraData, Oracle databases and Hadoop. ETL being run through multiple Informatica Grids.
Responsibility:

column2: Manage the L1 team (24x7 shift support) completely based in India and L2 team based in India and USA.
Track failures, identify bugs and manage the Jira Bug Queue with Development teams for fast resolution.
Define Production standards/requirements, best practices from Ops perspective and guide L1/L2 team with immediate and long-term fixes.
Manage Stakeholders and multi-level SLAs.

column1: Tools: Teradata, Oracle, Informatica, BTeq, Hadoop, Jira.
DM Release Engineering and Tools -

Data Management RE team manages the daily releases of Developers into all Production systems which includes releases of Informatica, DDLs, BTeqs, Shell/Perl Scripts. With Data Management being a very dynamic development team, RE handles 200+ releases per month. RE Team and Tools Team’s automations allows RE to scale to such a high level supporting so many systems across many security zones. Tools team also has developed many automation tools for sanity checking (TAT), Dependency assessment(TDAT), One-Click Load(OCL) for forklifts, Ops Tracker Tool for Failure tracking etc.', u'end_date': u'2014-08-01T00:00:00.000Z', u'title': u'Data Management Manager', u'company': {u'url': u'http://www.linkedin.com/company/1482?trk=ppro_cprof', u'_id': None, u'linkedin_id': 1482, u'name': u'PayPal'}, u'current': False, u'location': {u'freebase_id': u'/m/0c8tk', u'normalized': True, u'name': u'Chennai'}, u'start_date': u'2012-07-01T00:00:00.000Z'}, {u'description': u'As a Project Manager and Tech specialist, I am responsible for managing complex IT development projects and delivering them end to end, working with both India and UK resources. It encompasses governance of the project, people management and defining the right technical solution with hands on responsibilities.
Project(Development) – Optimizing Finance Project(OFP) (Dec 2009 – June 2011)

Group Finance is one of the horizontal department of RBS, which runs across all RBS group of banks. This project’s goal is to collect all the common data from different applications from different banks in the group and store in a Data warehouse for common use.
Tools: Informatica, Oracle 9i, ClearCase.
Project(Development) – AML Wealth (July 2010 – June 2011)

Anti Money Laundering has become a critical component of many Banks as they adapt to more stringent regulatory requirements being set by several countries. In this project two new groups of RBS were going to use Avaloq as their financial system and provide feeds to Fortent system for Transaction Monitoring.
Tools: Fortent 5.5, Informatica, Perl, Shell, Oracle 9i, ClearCase.
Project(Development) – Tesco Bank Separation Project (April 2010 – June 2011)

Tesco Bank separated from RBS group. As it was part of RBS, many of its data was feeding into RBS applications along with data from other streams. As part of separation, Tesco wanted extracts of its data present in several applications to build their own applications; Also RBS wanted to stop processing Tesco related data.

Tools: Fortent 7, NORKOM, Shell, Oracle 9i, ClearCase.', u'end_date': u'2011-06-01T00:00:00.000Z', u'title': u'Development Manager', u'company': {u'url': u'http://www.linkedin.com/company/1730?trk=ppro_cprof', u'_id': None, u'linkedin_id': 1730, u'name': u'Royal Bank of Scotland'}, u'current': False, u'location': {u'normalized': False, u'name': u''}, u'start_date': u'2009-12-01T00:00:00.000Z'}, {u'description': u'Role – Team Manager & Lead, Data Warehousing Team, India

As an India Team Manager and Project Lead, I was responsible for building the DataWarehouse team in India along with hands on responsibility of development and management of the applications supported by the global team.
Project(Development) – Prime Services Commodities
Commodities Trading is a new addition to Credit Suisse Prime Services Business. To provide IT support to the clients, we built an integrated system which

column2: Interfaces with a Sunguard transfer agency system, GMI, and collects trade information of our clients in the form of XMLs form MQ Series.
Transforms the data and format using Informatica (involving XML source, XML Generator, XML target transformations) to be readable by Kiodex, a Sunguard risk and position calculation engine.
Interfaces with Kiodex and collects greeks, Position and other information.
Processes and reports the data, through Data Warehouse, to the clients for their trades, so that they can make intelligent decisions.

column1: Tools: Informatica 7.1/8.1, Perl, Shell, Solaris 7.0, Oracle 9i, Sybase, Control-M, ClearCase.
Project(BAU) – Prime Services Data Warehouse(PSDW)
Credit Suisse started building a new team in India as an extension of existing Data Warehouse team in NY. As a Project Lead and Manager of the Indian team, I built the BAU / Lights On team in Pune.

Co-ordination: Reallocation work between the various sections and segments of organization. Coordinate with Asset Management Company, Investor Service Center and Call Center.

Handling Transactions: Managing daily payout process, daily funding process and controls. Controlling payout releases as well as checking transactions, processes, outputs and back ups at periodic intervals to maintain accuracy of transaction processing.

Reporting and Monitoring: Preparing monthly MIS on Assets Management (AUM), Scheme Performance, Scheme Net Asset Movement, AMC region Movement and other general reports. Managing and monitoring special products action on month wise (Ex., SIP, SWP, Triggers, STP) and preparing the relevant process for monthly audit.
Performance Monitoring: Monitoring and promoting productivity, higher quality of team performance and continuous improvement. Ensuring service deliverables as per SLA requirements at all times.
Remote site Operations Management: Managing the remote site operations for handling the daily transactions processing.

column2: Responsible for developing work plans, establishing objectives, assigning tasks, and managing groups/teams. Maintains schedules and coordinates activities of an entire group or department.
Develop full-scale project plans and associated communications documents. Effectively communicate project expectations to team members and stakeholders in a timely and clear fashion.
Implementation of project plans within pre-set budgets and deadlines.
Monitoring and executing projects with respect to budgeted cost, demand forecasts, time over-runs to ensure timely execution of projects ensuring technical and functional objectives are met.
Manages day-to-day client interaction. Sets and manages client expectations. Continually seeks opportunities to increase customer satisfaction and deepen client relationships.
Delegate tasks and responsibilities to appropriate personnel. Identify and resolve issues and conflicts within the project team. Identify and manage project dependencies
Identifies and recommends changes to established practices and policies.
Proactively manage changes in project scope, identify potential crises, and devise contingency plans.
Build, develop, and grow any business relationships vital to the success of the project.
Builds a knowledge base of each client's business, organization and objectives. Play key role in driving more revenue to the company by funneling more business.

From bug statistics to test coverage metrics to performance statistics, we often find ourselves up to our elbows in spreadsheets and graphs trying to help others visualize what we have found. But one question might always be asked, why is such kind of graphs necessary. Or rather, why is such analysis necessary? There is a saying that data doesn't lie. The defects logged contains a wealth of information which interpreted appropriately tells us all the good things and the areas of improvement in the arena of defect analysis and prevention. It also may be true that raw data doesn't lie. But it does not tell a story either. When we convert raw data into charts and graphs, we imbue the data with meaning. And like it or not, how we design our graphs has a big effect on the story that the data tells.

First we have to decide on which of the many possible stories embedded in the bug data we have to tell. Our ultimate aim should be to minimize the incidence of defects. The stories that the graphs tell us should be incorporated back into our process so that we are in a stage of continuous improvement of quality. What we are actually doing here is preventing the injection of defects into the product.', u'title': u'Advantages of defect analysis'}]",[],9.0,," Experienced customer requirements consultant, Certified Scrum Product Owner and Certified ScrumMaster

Subjects received pasireotide SC (single dose, 600 μg) on day 1, and samples for pharmacokinetics evaluation were collected from days 1 to 8. Subjects received an oral dose of verapamil 240 mg/d for 10 days (days 15-24). On day 18, subjects also received pasireotide SC 600 μg. Pharmacokinetic sampling for pasireotide SC and verapamil was done during days 18 to 25 and days 15 to 21, respectively. Safety evaluations were performed throughout the study period, including a 30-day post-treatment follow-up. Pharmacokinetic profiles of pasireotide SC alone and in combination with verapamil sustained-release (SR) were superimposable with the geometric mean ratios (90% confidence interval [CI]) of 0.98 (0.91-1.06) for C(max), 0.97 (0.90-1.04) for AUC(last), and 0.98 (0.92-1.05) for AUC(inf). Exploratory analyses showed a 17% (90% CI, 0.72-0.94) reduction in C(trough) and 31% (0.58-0.82) reduction in C(max) (8 hours post-dose) for verapamil SR with pasireotide SC versus verapamil alone. Pasireotide SC with or without verapamil was well tolerated. In conclusion, there was no change in the rate of pasireotide absorption and elimination or extent of exposure following concomitant administration with verapamil.', u'title': u'Effect of Verapamil on the Pharmacokinetics of Pasireotide in Healthy Volunteers', u'url': u'http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24788408&urlhash=2Sb4&trk=prof-publication-title-link', u'authors': [], u'date': u'2014-05-01T00:00:00.000Z'}]",1.0,"[Biostatistics, PK/PD, Exploratory Data..., Oncology, SAS programming, Clinical Study Design, Clinical Trials, Data Management, Clinical Research, SAS, Statistics, Protocol, SPSS, Pharmaceutical Industry, Analytics, Lifesciences, Biotechnology, Data Analysis, Clinical Development, Statistical Modeling, Logistic Regression, R, Pharmacokinetics, Clinical Data Management, CRO, Epidemiology, CRF design, CDISC, EDC, ICH-GCP, Pharmacodynamics, GCP, SDTM, Regulatory Submissions, Survival Analysis, Pharmacovigilance, CTMS, Medical Writing, Validation, Drug Development, Oracle Clinical, PK/PD modelling, Statistical Programming, Statistical Consulting, Therapeutic Areas, 21 CFR Part 11, SOP, FDA, Biomarkers, Pharmaceutics]","Professional Goal:

Mayberry,'}, {u'name': u'S. Mellone,'}, {u'name': u'C. Tacconi,'}, {u'url': u'http://www.linkedin.com/pub/alaga-raja-s-r/13/b50/b1b', u'name': u'ALAGA RAJA S R'}, {u'name': u'L. Rocchi,'}, {u'name': u'L. Chiari'}], u'description': u'Walking to a steady beat may increase step time variability, and it disrupts the long-term ‘fractal-like’ patterns in gait stride variability. The implications of these findings are still being explored, but the intent to follow a steady beat seems to alter the smooth, repeatable nature of gait in some way. Two measures attempting to describe smoothness have previously been applied to movement acceleration data. Jerk Index (JI), using the time derivative of acceleration, indicates ‘jerkiness’; JI is higher when subjects are paced by a metronome than when they tap freely. Harmonic Ratio (HR) compares the acceleration signal’s even and odd harmonic components, essentially quantifying the gait cycle’s repeatability; it is lower for older subjects or in a dual task condition. In this project we compare the JI and HR of gait a) in time with the beat (synchronized) and b) counter-phase to the beat (syncopated). Our goals are to explore the changes in gait during the challenging syncopated condition, and to better understand the relationship between JI and HR, which to our knowledge have not been directly compared.', u'title': u'How does walking with (or against) a metronome beat affect gait?'}]",,"[Matlab, sunny design, PVSyst, C, Keil, 8051 Microcontroller, Linux]","•

Bamboo is the most important non-wood species which is abundantly grows in most of the tropical and subtropical zone. It has developed as a specially valuable and superior alternate for wood composite manufactured, such as for pulp and paper, stripboards, matboards, veneer, plywood, particleboard and fiberboard. Moreover, several researches have used it as raw material for structural composites such as Oriented Strand Board (OSB), Glue Laminated Timber (GLT), Parallel Strip Lumber (PSL) and Oriented Strand Lumber (OSL). Nowadays, there are many kinds of bamboo composite are produced and traded in the world. However, there are several differences between bamboo and wood for example macroscopic and microscopic characteristics, chemical composition, physical and mechanical properties. For this reason, the methods, technology and equipment for wood processing cannot be directly applied in bamboo utilization. Further research is noticeably required on the information on bamboo properties, cost-effective technologies and managements. With modern techniques and adapted technologies, bamboo can be processed into a wide range of products which successfully compete with wood and other raw materials in the future.
